Anna Malenfant (October 16, 1902 – June 15, 1988) was a Canadian singer, educator and composer.
Anna Malenfant (October 16, 1902 – June 15, 1988) was a Canadian singer, educator and composer.
On her return to North America in 1929, she sang on radio station WITC in Hartford, Connecticut for a year under the name Louise Malmont.
On her return to North America in 1929, she sang on radio station WITC in Hartford, Connecticut for a year under the name Louise Malmont.
She studied with Salvator Issaurel in Montreal from 1930 to 1939.
In 1932, with Ludovic Huot and Lionel Daunais, she founded the Trio lyrique.
After 1944, she mainly performed in recitals and also taught.
In 1958, she received a Canada Council grant which allowed her to further develop her vocal technique in Rome.
In 2001, a documentary Anna Malenfant d'Acadie was produced based on archival material.
